# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lag-compensation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] In serial communication, clock synchronization can refer to clock recovery, which achieves frequency synchronization, as opposed to full phase synchronization.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Such clock synchronization is used in synchronization in telecommunications and automatic baud rate detection.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Plesiochronous or isochronous operation refers to a system with frequency synchronization and loose constraints on phase synchronization.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Synchronous operation implies a tighter synchronization based on time perhaps in addition to frequency.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] As a result of the difficulties managing time at smaller scales, there are problems associated with clock skew that take on more complexity in distributed computing in which several computers will need to realize the same global time.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] For instance, in Unix systems, the *make* command is used to compile new or modified code and seeks to avoid recompiling unchanged code.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The *make* command uses the clock of the machine it runs on to determine which source files need to be recompiled.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] If the sources reside on a separate file server and the two machines have unsynchronized clocks, the *make* program might not produce the correct results.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Synchronization is required for accurate reproduction of streaming media.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Clock synchronization is a significant component of audio over Ethernet systems.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] In a system with a central server, the synchronization solution is trivial; the server will dictate the system time.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Cristian's algorithm and the Berkeley algorithm are potential solutions to the clock synchronization problem in this environment.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] In distributed computing, the problem takes on more complexity because a global time is not easily known.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The most used clock synchronization solution on the Internet is the Network Time Protocol (NTP), which is a layered client-server architecture based on User Datagram Protocol (UDP) message passing.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Lamport timestamps and vector clocks are concepts of the logical clock in distributed computing.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] In a wireless network, the problem becomes even more challenging due to the possibility of collision of the synchronization packets on the wireless medium and the higher drift rate of clocks on low-cost wireless devices.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The Berkeley algorithm is suitable for systems where a radio clock is not present.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] This system has no way of making sure of the actual time other than by maintaining a global average time as the global time.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] A time server will periodically fetch the time from all the time clients, average the results, and then report back to the clients the adjustment that needs be made to their local clocks to achieve the average.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] This algorithm highlights the fact that internal clocks may vary not only in the time they contain but also in the clock rate.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Clock-sampling mutual network synchronization (CS-MNS) is suitable for distributed and mobile applications.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] It has been shown to be scalable over mesh networks that include indirectly-linked non-adjacent nodes and is compatible with IEEE 802.11 and similar standards.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] It can be accurate to the order of a few microseconds but requires direct physical wireless connectivity with negligible link delay (less than 1 microsecond) on links between adjacent nodes, limiting the distance between neighboring nodes to a few hundred meters.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Cristian's algorithm relies on the existence of a time server.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The time server maintains its clock by using a radio clock or other accurate time source, then all other computers in the system stay synchronized with it.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] A time client will maintain its clock by making a procedure call to the time server.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Variations of this algorithm make more precise time calculations by factoring in network radio propagation time.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] In addition to its use in navigation, the Global Positioning System (GPS) can also be used for clock synchronization.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The accuracy of GPS time signals is ±10 nanoseconds.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Using GPS (or other satellite navigation systems) for synchronization requires a receiver connected to an antenna with unobstructed view of the sky.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] IRIG timecodes are standard formats for transferring timing information.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Atomic frequency standards and GPS receivers designed for precision timing are often equipped with an IRIG output.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The standards were created by the Telecommunications Working Group of the United States military's Inter-Range Instrumentation Group (IRIG), the standards body of the Range Commanders Council.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Work on these standards started in October 1956, and the original standards were accepted in 1960.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Network Time Protocol (NTP) is a highly robust protocol, widely deployed throughout the Internet.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Well tested over the years, it is generally regarded as the state of the art in distributed time synchronization protocols for unreliable networks.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] It can reduce synchronization offsets to times of the order of a few milliseconds over the public Internet and to sub-millisecond levels over local area networks.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] A simplified version of the NTP protocol, Simple Network Time Protocol (SNTP), can also be used as a pure single-shot stateless primary/secondary synchronization protocol, but lacks the sophisticated features of NTP, and thus has much lower performance and reliability levels.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Precision Time Protocol (PTP) is a master/slave protocol for delivery of highly accurate time over local area networks.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The Reference Broadcast Time Synchronization (RBS) algorithm is often used in wireless networks and sensor networks.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] In this scheme, an initiator broadcasts a reference message to urge the receivers to adjust their clocks.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The Reference Broadcast Infrastructure Synchronization (RBIS) protocol is a master/slave synchronization protocol, like RBS, based on a receiver/receiver synchronization paradigm.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] It is specifically tailored to be used in IEEE 802.11 wireless networks configured in infrastructure mode (i.e., coordinated by an access point).
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The protocol does not require any modification to the access point.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Synchronous Ethernet uses Ethernet in a synchronous manner such that when combined with synchronization protocols such as PTP in the case of the White Rabbit Project, sub-nanosecond synchronization accuracy is achieved.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Synchronization is achieved in wireless ad hoc networks through sending synchronization messages in a multi-hop manner and each node progressively synchronizing with the node that is the immediate sender of a synchronization message.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Examples include Flooding Time Synchronization Protocol (FTSP), and Harmonia, both able to achieve synchronization with accuracy on the order of microseconds.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Researchers from Stanford and Google introduced Huygens, a probe-based, end-to-end clock synchronization algorithm.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] Huygens is implemented in software and thus can be deployed in data centers or in public cloud environments.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] By leveraging some key aspects of modern data centers and applying novel estimation algorithms and signal processing techniques, the Huygens algorithm achieved an accuracy of tens of nanoseconds even at high network load.
[src:lag-compensation/clock-synchronization] The findings of this research are being tested in financial market applications.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **interpolation** is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] It is often required to **interpolate**; that is, estimate the value of that function for an intermediate value of the independent variable.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] A closely related problem is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Suppose the formula for some given function is known, but too complicated to evaluate efficiently.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] A few data points from the original function can be interpolated to produce a simpler function which is still fairly close to the original.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The resulting gain in simplicity may outweigh the loss from interpolation error and give better performance in calculation process.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] As an example we will use points from the equation $f(x)=sin(x)$ to demonstrate various interpolation methods.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] We describe some methods of interpolation, differing in such properties as: accuracy, cost, number of data points needed, and smoothness of the resulting interpolant function.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The simplest interpolation method is to locate the nearest data value, and assign the same value.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In simple problems, this method is unlikely to be used, as linear interpolation (see below) is almost as easy, but in higher-dimensional multivariate interpolation, this could be a favourable choice for its speed and simplicity.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] One of the simplest methods is linear interpolation (sometimes known as lerp).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Consider the above example of estimating *f*(2.5).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Linear interpolation is quick and easy, but it is not very precise.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Another disadvantage is that the interpolant is not differentiable at the point *x**k*.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The following error estimate shows that linear interpolation is not very precise.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Denote the function which we want to interpolate by *g*, and suppose that *x* lies between *x**a* and *x**b* and that *g* is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In words, the error is proportional to the square of the distance between the data points.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The error in some other methods, including polynomial interpolation and spline interpolation (described below), is proportional to higher powers of the distance between the data points.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] These methods also produce smoother interpolants.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation is a generalization of linear interpolation.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Note that the linear interpolant is a linear function.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] We now replace this interpolant with a polynomial of higher degree.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Generally, if we have *n* data points, there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most *n*−1 going through all the data points.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The interpolation error is proportional to the distance between the data points to the power *n*.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Furthermore, the interpolant is a polynomial and thus infinitely differentiable.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] So, we see that polynomial interpolation overcomes most of the problems of linear interpolation.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] However, polynomial interpolation also has some disadvantages.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Calculating the interpolating polynomial is computationally expensive (see computational complexity) compared to linear interpolation.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Furthermore, polynomial interpolation may exhibit oscillatory artifacts, especially at the end points (see Runge's phenomenon).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation can estimate local maxima and minima that are outside the range of the samples, unlike linear interpolation.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] However, these maxima and minima may exceed the theoretical range of the function; for example, a function that is always positive may have an interpolant with negative values, and whose inverse therefore contains false vertical asymptotes.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] More generally, the shape of the resulting curve, especially for very high or low values of the independent variable, may be contrary to commonsense; that is, to what is known about the experimental system which has generated the data points.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] These disadvantages can be reduced by using spline interpolation or restricting attention to Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Linear interpolation uses a linear function for each of intervals [*x**k*,*x**k+1*].
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Spline interpolation uses low-degree polynomials in each of the intervals, and chooses the polynomial pieces such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The resulting function is called a spline.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] For instance, the natural cubic spline is piecewise cubic and twice continuously differentiable.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Furthermore, its second derivative is zero at the end points.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Like polynomial interpolation, spline interpolation incurs a smaller error than linear interpolation, while the interpolant is smoother and easier to evaluate than the high-degree polynomials used in polynomial interpolation.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] However, the global nature of the basis functions leads to ill-conditioning.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] This is completely mitigated by using splines of compact support, such as are implemented in Boost.Math and discussed in Kress.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Depending on the underlying discretisation of fields, different interpolants may be required.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In contrast to other interpolation methods, which estimate functions on target points, mimetic interpolation evaluates the integral of fields on target lines, areas or volumes, depending on the type of field (scalar, vector, pseudo-vector or pseudo-scalar).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] A key feature of mimetic interpolation is that vector calculus identities are satisfied, including Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] As a result, mimetic interpolation conserves line, area and volume integrals.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Conservation of line integrals might be desirable when interpolating the electric field, for instance, since the line integral gives the electric potential difference at the endpoints of the integration path.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation ensures that the error of estimating the line integral of an electric field is the same as the error obtained by interpolating the potential at the end points of the integration path, regardless of the length of the integration path.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Linear, bilinear and trilinear interpolation are also considered mimetic, even if it is the field values that are conserved (not the integral of the field).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Apart from linear interpolation, area weighted interpolation can be considered one of the first mimetic interpolation methods to have been developed.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The Theory of Functional Connections (TFC) is a mathematical framework specifically developed for functional interpolation.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Given any interpolant that satisfies a set of constraints, TFC derives a functional that represents the entire family of interpolants satisfying those constraints, including those that are discontinuous or partially defined.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] These functionals identify the subspace of functions where the solution to a constrained optimization problem resides.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Consequently, TFC transforms constrained optimization problems into equivalent unconstrained formulations.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] This transformation has proven highly effective in the solution of differential equations.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] TFC achieves this by constructing a constrained functional (a function of a free function), that inherently satisfies given constraints regardless of the expression of the free function.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] This simplifies solving various types of equations and significantly improves the efficiency and accuracy of methods like Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] TFC offers advantages over traditional methods like Lagrange multipliers and spectral methods by directly addressing constraints analytically and avoiding iterative procedures, although it cannot currently handle inequality constraints.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Interpolation is a common way to approximate functions.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Given a function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ with a set of points $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in [a,b]$ one can form a function $s:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ such that $f(x_{i})=s(x_{i})$ for $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ (that is, that s interpolates f at these points).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In general, an interpolant need not be a good approximation, but there are well known and often reasonable conditions where it will.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] For example, if $f\in C^{4}([a,b])$ (four times continuously differentiable) then cubic spline interpolation has an error bound given by $\|f-s\|_{\infty }\leq C\|f^{(4)}\|_{\infty }h^{4}$ where $h\max _{i=1,2,\dots ,n-1}|x_{i+1}-x_{i}|$ and C is a constant.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Gaussian process is a powerful non-linear interpolation tool.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Many popular interpolation tools are actually equivalent to particular Gaussian processes.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Gaussian processes can be used not only for fitting an interpolant that passes exactly through the given data points but also for regression; that is, for fitting a curve through noisy data.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In the geostatistics community Gaussian process regression is also known as Kriging.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW) is a spatial interpolation method that estimates values based on nearby data points, with closer points having more influence.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] It uses an inverse power law for weighting, where higher power values emphasize local effects, while lower values create a smoother surface.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] IDW is widely used in GIS, meteorology, and environmental modeling for its simplicity but may produce artifacts in clustered or uneven data.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Other forms of interpolation can be constructed by picking a different class of interpolants.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] For instance, rational interpolation is **interpolation** by rational functions using Padé approximant, and trigonometric interpolation is interpolation by trigonometric polynomials using Fourier series.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula can be used if the number of data points is infinite or if the function to be interpolated has compact support.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Sometimes, we know not only the value of the function that we want to interpolate, at some points, but also its derivative.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] This leads to Hermite interpolation problems.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] When each data point is itself a function, it can be useful to see the interpolation problem as a partial advection problem between each data point.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] This idea leads to the displacement interpolation problem used in transportation theory.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Multivariate interpolation is the interpolation of functions of more than one variable.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Methods include nearest-neighbor interpolation, bilinear interpolation and bicubic interpolation in two dimensions, and trilinear interpolation in three dimensions.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] They can be applied to gridded or scattered data.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation generalizes to n dimensional spaces where $n>3$ .
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In this application there is a specific requirement that the harmonic content of the original signal be preserved without creating aliased harmonic content of the original signal above the original Nyquist limit of the signal (that is, above fs/2 of the original signal sample rate).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] An early and fairly elementary discussion on this subject can be found in Rabiner and Crochiere's book *Multirate Digital Signal Processing*.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The term *extrapolation* is used to find data points outside the range of known data points.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In curve fitting problems, the constraint that the interpolant has to go exactly through the data points is relaxed.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] It is only required to approach the data points as closely as possible (within some other constraints).
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] This requires parameterizing the potential interpolants and having some way of measuring the error.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] In the simplest case this leads to least squares approximation.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] Approximation theory studies how to find the best approximation to a given function by another function from some predetermined class, and how good this approximation is.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] This clearly yields a bound on how well the interpolant can approximate the unknown function.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] If we consider x as a variable in a topological space, and the function $f(x)$ mapping to a Banach space, then the problem is treated as "interpolation of operators".
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] The classical results about interpolation of operators are the Riesz–Thorin theorem and the Marcinkiewicz theorem.
[src:lag-compensation/interpolation] There are also many other subsequent results.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:lag-compensation/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Players often blame "bad netcode" when they experience lag or reverse state transitions when synchronization between players is lost.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Although these events are sometimes caused by bugs, other networking-related causes include high latency between server and client, packet loss, or network congestion.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Depending on the game implementation, these issues can also be caused by non-network factors such as frame rendering time or inconsistent frame rate.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Netcode is often designed to mask networking irregularities and create a synchronous and smooth gamestate across multiple users.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] There are two main resolutions to this conflict implemented in modern games: delay-based and rollback-based resolution.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] The classic solution to this problem is the use of a delay-based netcode.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] When the inputs of a remote player arrive late, the game delays the inputs of the local player accordingly to synchronize the two inputs and run them simultaneously.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] This added delay can be disruptive for players (especially when latency is high), but overall the change is not very noticeable.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] However, these delays can be inconsistent due to sudden fluctuations in current latency.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Should the latency between players exceed an established buffer window for the remote player, the game must wait, causing the screens to "freeze".
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] This occurs because a delay-based netcode does not allow the simulation to continue until it receives the inputs from all the players in the frame in question.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] This variable delay causes an inconsistent and unresponsive experience compared to offline play (or to a LAN game), and can negatively affect player performance in timing-sensitive and fast-paced genres such as fighting games.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] An alternative system to the previous netcode is rollback netcode.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Some games utilize a hybrid solution in order to disguise these "jumps" (which can become problematic as latency between players grows, as there is less and less time to react to other players' actions) with a fixed input delay and then rollback being used.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Rollback is quite effective at concealing lag spikes or other issues related to inconsistencies in the users' connections, as predictions are often correct and players do not even notice.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Nevertheless, this system can be troublesome whenever a client's game slows down (usually due to overheating), since rift problems can be caused leading to an exchange of tickets between machines at unequal rates.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] This generates visual glitches that interrupt the gameplay of those players that receive inputs at a slower pace, while the player whose game is slowed down will have an advantage over the rest by receiving inputs from others at a normal rate (this is known as one-sided rollback).
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] There is a popular MIT-licensed library named GGPO designed to help implement rollback networking to games (mainly fighting games).
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Latency is unavoidable in online games, and the quality of the player's experience is strictly tied to this (the more latency there is between players, the greater the feeling that the game is not responsive to their inputs).
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] The latency of the players' network (which is largely out of a game's control) is not the only factor in question, but also the latency inherent in the way the game simulations are run.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] There are several lag compensation methods used to disguise or cope with latency (especially with high latency values).
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] A single update of a game simulation is known as a tick.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] The rate at which the simulation is run on a server is often referred to as the server's tickrate; this is essentially the server equivalent of a client's frame rate, absent any rendering system.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Tickrate is limited by the length of time it takes to run the simulation, and is often intentionally limited further to reduce instability introduced by a fluctuating tickrate, and to reduce CPU and data transmission costs.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] A lower tickrate increases latency in the synchronization of the game simulation between the server and clients.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] A lower tickrate also naturally reduces the precision of the simulation, which itself might cause problems if taken too far, or if the client and server simulations are running at significantly different rates.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Because of limitations in the amount of available bandwidth and the CPU time that's taken by network communication, some games prioritize certain vital communications while limiting the frequency and priority of less important information.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] As with tickrate, this effectively increases synchronization latency.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Game engines may limit the number of times that updates (of a simulation) are sent to a particular client and/or particular objects in the game's world in addition to reducing the precision of some values sent over the network to help with bandwidth use.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] This lack of precision may in some instances be noticeable.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] Various simulation synchronization errors between machines can also fall under the "netcode issues" blanket.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] These may include bugs which cause the simulation to proceed differently on one machine than on another, or which cause some things to not be communicated when the user perceives that they ought to be.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] A game's choice of transport layer protocol (and its management and coding) can also affect perceived networking issues.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] If a game uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), there will be increased latency between players.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] This protocol is based on the connection between two machines, in which they can exchange data and read it.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] These types of connections are very reliable, stable, ordered and easy to implement.
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] This type of protocol also tends to respond very slowly whenever they lose a packet, or when packets arrive in an incorrect order or duplicated, which can be very detrimental to a real-time online game (this protocol was not designed for this type of software).
[src:lag-compensation/netcode] If the game instead uses a User Datagram Protocol (UDP), the connection between machines will be very fast, because instead of establishing a connection between them the data will be sent and received directly.
[src:lag-compensation/network-delay] A certain minimum level of delay is experienced by signals due to the time it takes to transmit a packet serially through a link.
[src:lag-compensation/network-delay] This delay is extended by more variable levels of delay due to network congestion.
[src:lag-compensation/network-delay] IP network delays can range from a few milliseconds to several hundred milliseconds.
[src:lag-compensation/network-delay] For example, the hop count between two communication endpoints (such as server and client), may affect network delay.
